From: Michael Bangs <Michael_Bangs@fmi.com> [edited]


[Re: ProMED-mail Scrub typhus - Thailand 20141126.2992519]
----------------------------------------------------------
The wording of the sentence, "The cutaneous reaction to chiggers leaves a characteristic black eschar that is useful for making the diagnosis," is misleading.

The eschar (ulceration) is not the result of a reaction to a chigger bite per se, but rather the rickettsial organism (_Orientia tsutsugamushi_, etiologic agent of scrub typhus) that is transmitted as the result of the bite of an infected mite. The bites of uninfected chiggers often result in intense irritation (itch) but typically do not result in any form of secondary infection or complications. The word "infected" should be inserted before "chiggers".

--
Michael J Bangs, MSPH, PhD
Public Health & Malaria Control
International SOS
Kuala Kencana, Papua, Indonesia
<Michael_Bangs@fmi.com>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Bangs for this clarification. - Mod.LL

